{"text": " I have a question, if the police find the stolen pieces from the Louvre. How will they actually know that they're real and not fake? Imagine you're the thief, and you're trying to replicate this tiara. What's gonna get you caught is the pearls. For the diamonds, if you use voice and I, they'll just shine a light on it. So maybe you'll try lab-grown diamonds. They look identical. Until an expert uses UV light and lasers to show that the structure is too perfect. So you'd have to use natural diamonds, cut into exactly the right shape. Except natural diamonds have tiny minerals that were trapped in the gem when it formed. And that would have been a dead giveaway. If we'd made a scan of these diamonds before they were stolen. But we didn't do that. So you could fake the diamonds, but not the pearls. Because the inside of a pearl looks like this. Layers upon layers of a material that makes up an oyster or a muscle shell. And only the outermost layer is it arranged smoothly enough to give it that pearly glimmer. So you can't reshape a pearl to match this. And you can't grow one either because X-rays will easily identify that. And they might cut the diamonds down enough to successfully hide their origin. But I'm willing to bet that with technology will eventually find these pearls. If you like optimistic science and tech stories, follow along.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 3.8000000000000003, "text": " I have a question, if the police find the stolen pieces from the Louvre.", "tokens": [50364, 286, 362, 257, 1168, 11, 498, 264, 3804, 915, 264, 15900, 3755, 490, 264, 7272, 34869, 13, 50554], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14979275913103252, "compression_ratio": 1.6918238993710693, "no_speech_prob": 0.007174414116889238}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 3.8000000000000003, "end": 7.0, "text": " How will they actually know that they're real and not fake?", "tokens": [50554, 1012, 486, 436, 767, 458, 300, 436, 434, 957, 293, 406, 7592